{"source_key":"sha256-c8597aca71664a84bdd657ea13dadbd3","record_index":904,"record_hash":"sha256:9dd790c1eeb6303c68cadfff010aec9f921c0b5c35d4526cba279c49153dbbec","timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:11:16.499Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 599be2\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 3232\nOutput:\n# Session Association Strategy\n\n> [!NOTE]\n> This note is older background. The current association direction is\n> [Including Turns In Agentlog](Including-turns.md): no human-in-the-loop\n> association writes, capture-time observations plus derived lookup indexes,\n> and read-time association scoring. Keep this document for the reasoning about\n> why direct capture-time ownership and naive branch association are brittle.\n\nThis note explores how captured agent sessions could be connected to branches,\nchanges, commits, or pull requests. It is not an implementation plan. Its job is\nto compare paths, keep the brittle parts visible, and identify pragmatic\nshortcuts that support the two future use cases:\n\n- session handoff across machines or agents\n- review sharing through a GitButler timeline of relevant agent sessions\n\n## What We Want\n\nThe durable object is still the project-scoped agent session:\n\n```text\nproject\n  gitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:*\n```\n\nFuture review or branch objects should reference those sessions:\n\n```text\n<branch/change/commit/pr target>\n  gitbutler:agent-sessions = set<session-key>\n```\n\nThe relationship should mean \"this session is relevant to this target\", not\n\"this session uniquely generated this target\". That wording matters because the\nreal workflow is many-to-many:\n\n- one session can contribute to several branches or pull requests\n- one branch or pull request can involve several sessions\n- a session can be useful context even before any code exists\n- a session can contain useful discussion even if no generated code is kept\n\n## Key Constraint\n\nCapture-time association is weak evidence. The current branch may be wrong, a\nGitButler worktree can contain several active branches, and the user may later\nsplit generated edits across destinations. Capture should continue to write\nproject-scoped sessions and avoid inferred ownership.\n\nCommit, amend, and PR moments have better evidence, bu\n[TRUNCATED]\n of a patch/change.\n\nRisks to keep explicit:\n\n- synthetic change ids derived from commit ids are not durable across rewrites\n- two different pieces of content can share a change id over time\n- squash may keep one surviving change id and drop the others\n- uncommit/recommit can break the relationship unless the user confirms it again\n- plain Git operations can bypass GitButler's ability to maintain links\n\nIf automatic propagation becomes necessary, prefer one centralized association\noperation over scattered set mutations across every commit lifecycle path.\n\n## Open Questions\n\n- Which signals are strong enough to preselect a suggested session?\n- Should the commit UI ask the user to confirm suggested sessions?\n- Should PR/review publishing include a required or optional session picker?\n- Should GitButler track an explicit \"active agent session\" during a workspace\n  session?\n- How should non-GitButler Git operations be represented, if at all?\n- Should relationships be stored permanently, recomputed from evidence, or both?\n- How much uncertainty should be shown to reviewers?\n- What is the smallest centralized API that can keep association updates out of\n  every individual mutation path?\n\n## Cautious Direction\n\nDo not infer association at capture time.\n\nStart with explicit relationships and suggestion-assisted confirmation. The\nfirst high-value shortcut is likely a PR/review prep picker because it directly\nsupports review sharing without requiring lifecycle propagation. The next step,\nif code-level precision is needed, is confirmed change-id association with\nderived branch/PR views.\n\nKeep stored links coarse: \"these sessions are relevant\". Let readers derive\ntranscript windows later.\n\n## Extra\n\n\n`Capture time`\n- Checked out branch(es) - maintain a count\n- Files touched (uncommitted) - monotonically increasing set\n- For each checked out branch\n\t- files committed vs session files touched\n\n`env`\n\n```\n{\n\t\"checked_out_refs\": [\n\t\t\"feat\",\n\t\t\"bug-fix\",\n\t\t\"random\"\n\t],\n\t\"worktree_files\": [\n\t\t\"foo.py\",\n\t\t\"bar.txt\"\n\t]\n}\n```\n\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:11:16.499Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}